Assignment 4 - Transport

© Group 3 - Lena Gerstmans, Henrike Beckeveld & Tess van den Berg


Paris is hosting the Paralympics in 2024. One of the events at the Paralympics is an open water swimming event in the Seine (apparently the water is clean or so the French say). Since the City of Amsterdam thinks it is beter than Paris, they want to host an event before the Paralympics, snubbing the Parisians. The idea is to host a 5km. open water swimming event through the canals of Amsterdam. You are asked by the municipality of Amsterdam to advise on the feasibility of the event from the perspective of the safety of the partaking athletes from an environmental perspective. The event is going to be hosted in May.

The Municipality wants you to find a location for the Event Headquarters. They decided it would be best if this E.H. is as close to the centre of the swimming route. There is a bit of a concern for the after party and the stream of visitors. They want you to quantify the number o visitors that can reach the event and the capacity for festivites after the even*.

Assignment 4¶

For this exercise you have chosen a route in Amsterdam for the canal swimming event. Preferably you have this route calculated using Python. You can set a start point and an end point and then try to find a route that has a certain dista.***The distance of our chosen route is 5.1 km. Our guideline has been the existing route of the City Swim, so we are taking the finish line (at the AMS) as our starting point. This location is suitable for hosting an event like the Cityswim. The route around artis was chosen because it is an easily accessible but quiet water route. We have chosen to finish in the city centre near the Frederiksplein. This is because this location is easily accessible for all the people who come to watch, but also for the swimmers who take part. Looking at previous events that have taken place there, the Fredriksplein is also suitable for hosting an eve

Since we were not able to base our route upon water pollution, the existing route of the City Swim was taken as a start, as we knew there would be pollution level installations. The remaining route has been based upon accessibility for paralympic swimmers and the public. In addition, only a part of the Herengracht and Keizersgracht is used for the event. This means the canal boats can still go through the popular canals.

Q1 - Find the centre of the nodes of the swimming route. See this link.¶

The centre of the nodes of the swimming route was calculated by finding the central latitude and longitude points. Then, it was illustrated by finding the corresponding node of this coordinate. The map on which this is illustrated is of the road network of the centre of Amsterdam for easy readability.

# coordinates start (latitude and longitude)
lat = 52.3715052
lon = 4.9132839

# we take 840m for a 10 minute walk
walking_radius = 840

# extracting information about bus and trams stops (ways and nodes)
query = f"""
    [out:json];
    (
        node["public_transport"="stop_position"]
            (around:{walking_radius},{lat},{lon});
        way["public_transport"="platform"]
            (around:{walking_radius},{lat},{lon});
    );
    out center;
"""

api = overpy.Overpass()

result = api.query(query)

closest_stop = None
closest_distance = float('inf')

# finding the nearest stop
for node in result.nodes:
    location = (float(node.lat), float(node.lon))
    distance = ((lat - location[0])**2 + (lon - location[1])**2) ** 0.5
    if distance < closest_distance:
        closest_stop = node
        closest_distance = distance

for way in result.ways:
    location = (float(way.center_lat), float(way.center_lon))
    distance = ((lat - location[0])**2 + (lon - location[1])**2) ** 0.5
    if distance < closest_distance:
        closest_stop = way
        closest_distance = distance

# Print the closest stop
if closest_stop:
    if hasattr(closest_stop, 'tags'):
        name = closest_stop.tags.get("name", "Unknown")
        print(f'Closest Stop: {name}, Location: ({closest_stop.lat}, {closest_stop.lon})')
    else:
        print(f'Closest Stop: Unknown Location: ({closest_stop.center_lat}, {closest_stop.center_lon})')
else:
    print("No nearby bus or tram stops found within the specified radius.")

    [out:json];
    (
        node["public_transport"="stop_position"]
            (around:{walking_radius},{lat},{lon});
        way["public_transport"="platform"]
            (around:{walking_radius},{lat},{lon});
    );
    out center;
"""

api = overpy.Overpass()

result = api.query(query)

# Initialize variables to track the closest stop
closest_stop = None
closest_distance = float('inf')

# finding the closest stop
for node in result.nodes:
    location = (float(node.lat), float(node.lon))
    distance = ((lat - location[0])**2 + (lon - location[1])**2) ** 0.5
    if distance < closest_distance:
        closest_stop = node
        closest_distance = distance

for way in result.ways:
    location = (float(way.center_lat), float(way.center_lon))
    distance = ((lat - location[0])**2 + (lon - location[1])**2) ** 0.5
    if distance < closest_distance:
        closest_stop = way
        closest_distance = distance

# printing the closest stop
if closest_stop:
    if hasattr(closest_stop, 'tags'):
        name = closest_stop.tags.get("name", "Unknown")
        print(f'Closest Stop: {name}, Location: ({closest_stop.lat}, {closest_stop.lon})')
    else:
        print(f'Closest Stop: Unknown Location: ({closest_stop.center_lat}, {closest_stop.center_lon})')
else:
    print("No nearby bus or tram stops found within the specified radius.")

Q5 - Calculate the centrality of the start, finish, and centre node of the route.¶

Which centrality calculation makes the most sense. See this link.¶

Answer 5.¶

There are different ways in which one can calculate centrality.

For the starting and ending point, it is important that everyone can leave as smoothly as possible. Hence, it is important that everyone can reach other nodes quickly. The closeness centrality measures how close a node is to all other nodes in the network. A node with high closeness centrality will have the property that individuals at that location can quickly reach other nodes, which represents exit routes or paths.

For the central point, it is important that the organising team can easily access all nodes of the swimming route from the central point. Therefore, you want to measure how well-connected one node is to specific other nodes. The shortest path centrality calculates the shortest path from the head quarters node to the other nodes on the route. This consideres the efficiency of the headquarters node in reaching the swimming route nodes.

#Calculate the shortest path centrality of the HQ
north, south, east, west = 52.3911937, 52.3505111, 4.8618788, 4.9380764
graph_centre = ox.graph_from_bbox(north, south, east, west, network_type='all', simplify=True, custom_filter= None)

node_hq = 46359166
nodes_swimmingroute = [4360607277, 6815197368, 1244055734, 46353247, 46356661, 46355782, 46351183, 46363900, 46360980, 46347456, 46343363]

shortest_path_centrality = {}
for node in nodes_swimmingroute:
    if node == node_hq:
        continue  
    shortest_paths = nx.single_source_shortest_path_length(graph_centre, node_hq)
    
    if node in shortest_paths:
        centrality = 1 / sum(1 / length for length in shortest_paths.values() if length > 0)
        shortest_path_centrality[node] = round(centrality,4)
    else:
        shortest_path_centrality[node] = 0  

for node, centrality in shortest_path_centrality.items():
    print(f"Shortest Path Centrality from node head quarters node {node_hq} to node {node} on swimmingroute: {centrality}")
